categories.description: Promotional emails are messages designed to advertise, market, or promote a product, service, brand, or offer.  They usually come from businesses, online stores, or marketing teams and are intended to drive sales, engagement, or awareness.  🧠 Characteristics of Promotional Emails: 1. **Purpose** – To sell, promote, or create awareness of a product, service, discount, or event. 2. **Sender Type** – Usually from brand domains, marketing platforms, or newsletters (e.g., @amazon.in, @flipkart.com, @zomato.com, @mailchimp.com). 3. **Tone & Content** – Persuasive, enthusiastic, or sales-oriented language such as:    - “Limited-time offer!”    - “Get 50% off today!”    - “Introducing our new collection!”    - “Special discount for you!” 4. **Visual Layout** – Contain banners, product images, buttons like “Shop Now,” “Claim Offer,” or “Subscribe.” 5. **Frequency** – Often sent in bulk to multiple recipients or subscribers. 6. **Common Keywords** – “sale,” “offer,” “discount,” “exclusive,” “deal,” “subscribe,” “shop,” “promotion,” “limited time,” “coupon,” “save big,” etc. 7. **Attachments or Links** – Often contain promotional links, shopping links, or subscription links. 8. **Examples:**    - “Amazon Great Indian Festival starts now! Get 70% off electronics.”    - “Your Domino’s offer is waiting — 2 pizzas for ₹99!”    - “Special launch discount on our new AI course.”  ⚙️ **How to Categorize** If an email’s main purpose is advertising, promoting, or announcing a product, sale, service, or marketing campaign —  classify it as **"Promotional"** even if it includes greetings or personalization.  If it is informational, transactional (like order confirmation), or personal, **do not mark as promotional.**  🧩 **Output Example**

Spam emails are unwanted, irrelevant, or suspicious messages often sent in bulk to many recipients.   They usually have no legitimate relationship with the user and are often designed to deceive, scam, or promote low-quality, unrelated content.  🧠 Characteristics of Spam Emails: 1. **Purpose** – To mislead, scam, or flood inboxes with irrelevant or unsolicited promotions. 2. **Sender Type** – Unknown or suspicious email addresses, often with random characters or strange domains     (e.g., "abc123@cheapoffers.ru", "lottery@randomdomain.xyz"). 3. **Tone & Content** – Unusual, exaggerated, or manipulative language such as:    - “You’ve won a prize!”    - “Urgent! Update your password now!”    - “Claim your $1000 reward!”    - “This is your last chance to receive payment!” 4. **Common Intent** – To trick users into clicking malicious links, sharing sensitive info, or buying fake products. 5. **Visual Layout** – May contain poor formatting, spelling mistakes, fake branding, or suspicious links. 6. **Common Keywords & Phrases** –    “Congratulations,” “Winner,” “Lottery,” “Act now,” “Urgent,” “Click here,” “Verify account,”     “Free money,” “Risk-free,” “Guaranteed income,” “Get rich quick.” 7. **Links/Attachments** – Often contain phishing links or unsafe attachments (.exe, .zip, .scr). 8. **Examples:**    - “Congratulations! You’ve won a free iPhone! Click here to claim.”    - “Your bank account will be suspended. Verify your details immediately.”    - “Earn $500 per day from home — no experience needed!”  ⚙️ **How to Categorize** If the email seems deceptive, irrelevant, or sent without consent — and attempts to gain clicks, data, or money —  classify it as **"Spam"** even if it looks somewhat promotional.  If it comes from a verified sender or is part of a legitimate subscription, **do not mark as spam** (use “Promotional” instead).  🧩 **Output Example**

"Others" (also known as "General" or "Uncategorized") emails include all legitimate messages that  don’t clearly fall under Promotional, Spam, Transactional, or Informational/Updates categories.  🧠 Characteristics of “Other” Emails: 1. **Purpose** – To communicate general, one-to-one or small group messages     that are not promotional, automated, or spammy. 2. **Sender Type** – Usually real individuals, colleagues, or small teams.    May also include messages from unknown senders that seem authentic but not commercial or malicious. 3. **Tone & Content** – Neutral, conversational, or professional tone.     Examples:    - “Hey, can we reschedule our meeting?”    - “I wanted to follow up about your previous message.”    - “Here’s the document you requested.”    - “Let’s connect to discuss collaboration.” 4. **No Marketing or Automation Indicators** –     - No promotional offers, discounts, or marketing banners.    - No automated notifications (like receipts or password resets). 5. **Subject Examples** –    - “Follow-up on our chat”    - “Quick question for you”    - “Meeting notes from yesterday”    - “Job opportunity discussion” 6. **Attachments/Links** – Usually safe or work-related files (e.g., PDFs, Docs, presentations). 7. **Keywords & Phrases** – May include personal communication phrases:    “Hope you’re doing well,” “Let’s schedule,” “Following up,” “Attached below.”  ⚙️ **How to Categorize** If the email is neither promotional nor spammy, and not clearly a system-generated notification,  mark it as **“Other”**.   These are real, human-to-human communications or general inquiries.  🧩 **Output Example**

Personal promotional request emails are messages where the sender is reaching out to you directly to suggest, request, or offer a promotion, collaboration, or marketing opportunity. These emails often contain statements like 'I want a promotion,' 'Can you feature my content,' 'Collaboration proposal,' or 'Promotion opportunity.' The AI should identify such emails as 'Personal Promotional' and differentiate them from spam, automated notifications, or general inquiries."  🧠 Characteristics of Personal Promotional Requests:  Purpose – The sender is requesting a promotion, collaboration, sponsorship, or marketing opportunity directed at the recipient.  Sender Type – Usually individual content creators, influencers, small businesses, or marketers who directly contact you.  Tone & Content – Personal, persuasive, or professional tone, often referencing a desired promotion or collaboration. Examples:  “I’d like to promote my video on your channel.”  “Can you help promote our upcoming event?”  “Looking for a collaboration opportunity with your platform.”  Keywords & Phrases – “Promotion,” “collaboration,” “feature my content,” “sponsored,” “opportunity,” “partnership.”  Subject Examples –  “Promotion request for your channel”  “Collaboration opportunity for [Name]”  “Feature my content on your platform?”  ⚙️ How to Categorize If the email is a direct request or offer for promotion or collaboration, mark it as “Personal Promotional”. Ignore emails that are generic newsletters, spam, or transactional notifications.

parameters.text:
=You are a professional YouTube brand collaboration assistant for a large YouTube channel with a strong audience and high engagement.

Your task is to write a personalized, friendly, and persuasive follow-up email to a brand or person who previously collaborated for a promotion.

Use the following data:
- Brand or person's email: {{ $json.Gmail }}
- Reason for their last promotion: {{ $json.Reason }}

Your goal:
- Ask if they would like to collaborate again for another promotional campaign.
- Mention how their brand previously got visibility or engagement through the last promotion (use general positive tone).
- Highlight that there are new promotional formats, better reach, and audience engagement opportunities.
- Keep the email polite, short (under 120 words), and written in a conversational but professional tone.
- End with a simple call-to-action like: “Would you like to discuss a new promotion opportunity this week?”

snippet.title: Jesper Nissen SEO
snippet.description:
Hey there, my name is Jesper Nissen, and I have more than 17 years of experience in software testing, systems design, software engineering, webdesign and SEO.

I have a master degree in theoretical physics from the University of Copenhagen, Niels Bohr Institute. 

Although I don’t use my knowledge of quantum mechanics in my daily work, I have brought with me into the field of SEO, the scientific curiosity and ability to really focus and try to understand a subject in all details. And that is what I love about SEO, it’s a field of neverending discoveries.

I will share short training videos, link building tutorials, seo news and seo related stuff in my channel. I hope you like it and find it usable!

Best regards Jesper Nissen
